my:Hazard.my:ControlMeasures:
a) Use of suitable and appropriate PPE: overalls, safety shoes, hard hat, gloves, etc.; 
b) Approved boarding equipment must be used i.e. pilot ladder, accommodation ladder, gangway; 
c) A safety net must be rigged as per IMO regulations; 
d) All crew engaged in the rigging / stowing of the accommodation ladder / gangway are to wear a safety harness connected to the fall arrest equipment and don a lifejacket.

a) All crew involved with bunkering / sludge removal operations must be fully trained with the regard to the procedure; 
b) Use of suitable and appropriate PPE: overalls, safety shoes, hard hat, oil-resistant gloves, etc.; 
c) 'Bunkering / Sludge Removal Checklist' to be completed; 
d) Smoking is not permitted - Suitable warning notices to be posted; 
e) Ensure all initial fire-fighting appliances i.e. portable fire extinguisher are on stand-by; 
f) Hot work is not permitted during bunkering / sludge removal operations.

a) All crew involved with bunkering / sludge removal operations must be fully trained with the regard to the procedure; 
b) Use of suitable and appropriate PPE: overalls, safety shoes, hard hat, oil-resistant gloves, etc.; 
c) 'Bunkering / Sludge Removal Checklist' to be completed; 
d) Sufficient number of crew to be made available; 
e) Vessel's davit / cargo crane to assist, if necessary, in bringing the fuel line to the bunker station; 
f) Lines should be fitted to the fuel line to control or adjust the position; 
g) Consult 'Manual Handling' Risk Assessment.

a) Use of suitable and appropriate PPE: overalls, safety shoes, hard hat, oil-resistant gloves, goggles, etc.; 
b) All crew involved with bunkering / sludge removal operations must be fully trained with the regard to the procedure;
c) 'Bunkering / Sludge Removal Checklist' to be completed; 
d) SOPEP equipment i.e. clean-up materials, dispersants, etc., are on stand-by; d) Emergency stops / alarms tested and ready; 
e) Suitable warning notices to be posted; 
f) Adequate lighting to be provided. Use portable lighting if necessary; 
g) All reception tanks should be sounded prior to and during bunker operations; 
h) Ensure all scuppers are plugged; 
i) Ensure all save-alls are empty and in place; 
j) Any bunker connections not in use should be securely blanked; 
k) All fuel lines and connections must be visually inspected and connections checked and confirmed tight; 
l) Crew vigilance - Continuous watch to be maintained in both the E/R and bunker station / deck; 
m) Communication must be established, via VHF or signal, between the vessel and supplying installation i.e. shore side, barge; 
n) Fuel line connection to be plugged during transportation prior to and on completion of operations; 
o) Consult vessel's 'SOPEP Manual', if an oil spill occurs; 
p) Consult 'Dealing with Hazardous Substances' Risk Assessment, if necessary.

a) Adequate lighting to be provided. Use portable lighting if necessary; 
b) Ensure that the deck area and bunker station are free of any obstructions; 
c) Clean contaminated deck areas as soon as possible.
